'''Aidan Mackenzy "Aidy" Bryant''' (born May 7, 1987) is an American actress and comedian. She is best known as a cast member on the late-night variety series ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', beginning in [[Saturday Night Live (season 38)|season 38]].<ref name=chicagotribune>{{cite news|last=Metz|first=Nina|title=Aidy Bryant, Tim Robinson, Cecily Strong join cast of 'SNL'|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-10/entertainment/chi-join-cast-on-snl-20120910_1_snl-executive-producer-weekend-update-io-theater|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> For her work on the series, she has been nominated for two [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], including for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aidy Bryant - Awards - IMDb|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5262775/awards?ref_=nm_awd|accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref>
==Early life== Bryant was born on May 7, 1987 in [[Phoenix, Arizona]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://historiccentral.com/about-us/ |title=About Us |last=Bryant |first=Tom |date= |newspaper=Tom Bryant |access-date=February 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170207105841/http://historiccentral.com/about-us/ |archive-date=February 7, 2017 |dead-url=no |work= |language=en-US |via= }}</ref> the daughter of Georganna (née Vinall) and Tom Bryant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tucson/obituary.aspx?pid=172526415|title=Kenneth A. Vinall|date=September 21, 2014|publisher=Legacy.com|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Her mother owns a boutique called Frances in Phoenix.<ref name="phoenixnewtimes2013">{{Cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/arts/saturday-night-lives-aidy-bryant-on-real-housewives-addiction-and-how-kristen-wiigs-the-best-6577839|title=Saturday Night Live's Aidy Bryant on Real Housewives Addiction and How Kristen Wiig's The Best|last=Bartkowski|first=Becky|date=August 22, 2013|newspaper=Phoenix New Times|access-date=February 7, 2017}}</ref> Bryant is of English, Irish and German descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Aidy-Bryant/6000000035826269841?through=6000000035825830246 |title=Aidy Bryant |last=Caldwell-Gilbert |first=Tamás Flinn |date=July 28, 2016 |website=Geni.com |language=en-US |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170207110556/https://www.geni.com/people/Aidy-Bryant/6000000035826269841?through=6000000035825830246 |archive-date=February 7, 2017 |dead-url=no |access-date=February 7, 2017 }}</ref> She has one brother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/business/articles/2010/01/28/20100128work-life-balance-bryant.html |title=Georganne Bryant: Commit to a family day |publisher=azcentral.com |date=January 28, 2010 |accessdate=November 3, 2014 }}</ref> She graduated from [[Xavier College Preparatory (Arizona)|Xavier College Preparatory]] in 2005, where she made the morning announcements.<ref name="phoenixnewtimes2013" /> Bryant developed an interest in performing during middle school theater classes and summer camps, where she learned about [[improvisation]].<ref name="phoenixnewtimes2014">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/jackalope/2014/10/aidy_bryant_snl_phoenix.php |title=Aidy Bryant's Made It Big on Saturday Night Live, But Phoenix Still Feels Like Home |publisher=Phoenix New Times |date=October 2, 2014 |first=Claire |last=Lawton |accessdate=November 3, 2014 }}</ref> Her parents took her to improv workshops at the now-defunct Arizona Jewish Theatre Company.<ref name="phoenixnewtimes2014"/>
She graduated from [[Columbia College Chicago|Columbia College]] in [[Chicago]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in 2009.<ref name=NBC>{{cite web|title=Cast Bios|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/bios/aidy-bryant_38.shtml|work=Aidy Bryant|publisher=NBC|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name="columbiacollegechicago">{{cite web|url=http://theloop.colum.edu/s/644/index.aspx?sid=644&gid=25&pgid=252&cid=14129&ecid=14129&ciid=50986&crid=0 |title=Alumna Aidy Bryant Joins SNL Cast |publisher=Columbia College Chicago |accessdate=November 3, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103111551/http://theloop.colum.edu/s/644/index.aspx?sid=644&gid=25&pgid=252&cid=14129&ecid=14129&ciid=50986&crid=0 |archivedate=November 3, 2014 }}</ref> At Columbia College, she participated in the college's comedy studies program, developed by the Theatre Department and The Second City.<ref name="columbiacollegechicago"/>
==Career== After Bryant graduated from Columbia College, she toured with the musical improv group Baby Wants Candy and was approached by Second City.<ref name="phoenixnewtimes2014"/> She has performed with [[iO Chicago]], [[The Second City]]<ref name="dailybeast2014">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/10/31/how-aidy-bryant-stealthily-became-your-favorite-saturday-night-live-star.html |title=How Aidy Bryant Stealthily Became Your Favorite ‘Saturday Night Live’ Star |publisher=''[[The Daily Beast]]'' |date=October 31, 2014 |first=Kevin |last=Fallon |accessdate=November 3, 2014 }}</ref> and the [[Annoyance Theatre]]. She was a writer and ensemble member for both "Sky's the Limit, Weather Permitting" and "We're All In This Room Together" on the Second City e.t.c. Stage.<ref name=NBC/>
Bryant made her debut as a featured player on ''Saturday Night Live'' on September 15, 2012.<ref name=NBC/><ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|title='Saturday Night Live' adds three new cast members|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/Saturday-Night-Live-adds-three-new-cast-members-70000041/snl-adds-three-new-cast-members/70000041/1#.UFEhelGByS0|newspaper=USA Today|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=‘Saturday Night Live’ adds 3 performers for upcoming season after departures of Wiig, Samberg|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/saturday-night-live-adds-3-performers-for-upcoming-season-after-departures-of-wiig-samberg/2012/09/10/e1bc7170-fb5f-11e1-98c6-ec0a0a93f8eb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post (The Associated Press)|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> She was promoted to a repertory player during her second season on the show.
In 2013, Bryant appeared with a recurring role in the second season of [[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]]'s ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|Comedy Bang! Bang!]]'', playing the show's segment producer.<ref>[http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/comedy-bang-bang-andy-richter-wears-a-suit-jacket--101568 The A.V. Club]</ref> Bryant also made an uncredited cameo appearance in ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]''.<ref>[https://twitter.com/snltrivia/status/459513906918981632 Twitter]</ref> She has made guest appearances on programs such as ''[[Broad City]]'', ''[[Documentary Now!]]'', ''[[The Awesomes]]'', and ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''. In 2016, Bryant had a recurring role as Alice in the [[Louis C.K.]] series ''[[Horace and Pete]]''. In 2017, Bryant provided the voice of main character D.D. Danger on the animated series ''[[Danger & Eggs]]''.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/pennsylvania/articles/2017-07-23/johnstown-native-brings-egg-citement-to-kids-video</ref>
In 2014, Bryant, Eli Bruggemann, Chris Kelly, [[Sarah Schneider]], and [[Kate McKinnon]] were nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] in the category of [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics|Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics]] for the "Home for the Holiday (Twin Bed)". The music video sketch aired on December 21, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/aidy-bryant|title=Aidy Bryant|work=Television Academy|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref> She won the award for Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series at the 2015 EWwy awards which honor performances that were snubbed by the Emmys.<ref>http://ew.com/gallery/2015-ewwy-winners/best-supporting-actress-comedy</ref> In 2018, Bryant received a nomination at the [[70th Primetime Emmy Awards]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2018/outstanding-supporting-actress-in-a-comedy-series |title=Nominees/Winners &#124; Television Academy |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref>
